{
  "texts": [
    "Any modal formula that has a local/global first-order correspondent over all full possibility frames also has a local/global first-order correspondent over full world frames, viz., the same first-order formula, in which ⊑ may be replaced by =.Thus, the modal formulas that lack first-order correspondents over full world frames, e.g., Benthem, 1975, Goldblatt, 1975], also lack first-order correspondents over full possibility frames.",
    "This does not show, however, that such formulas lack a first-order correspondent over some restricted class of full possibility frames that does not include all full world frames, e.g., functional full frames ( § 4.4).□ i ♢ i p → ♢ i □ i p [vanThe converse question of whether every modal formula with a local/global first-order correspondent over full world frames also has one over full possibility frames is an open question (see § 8.2).We will consider both local and global correspondence as in Definition 6.8.",
    "By part 1 of the following obvious fact, having a local correspondent implies having a global one (part 2 will be useful later).",
    "Fact 6.14 (From Local to Global).",
    "For any φ, ψ ∈ L(Φ, I), δ(x) ∈ L 1 (I) with x free, and class F of possibility frames:1. if φ locally corresponds to δ(x) relative to F, then φ globally corresponds to ∀x δ(x) relative to F;2. if φ → ψ locally corresponds to ∀x ⊑ x 0 δ(x) relative to F, then φ → ψ globally corresponds to ∀x δ(x) relative to F.As in possible world semantics, so too in possibility semantics, having a global correspondent does not imply having a local correspondent."
  ]
}